    "title": "GovTech HMCTS Digital Witness Management — Crown Court Pilot",
    "metaTitle": "GovTech HMCTS Digital Witness Management — Crown Court Pilot — ClickMasters Case Study",
    "metaDesc": "An HMCTS-contracted digital supplier building a pilot digital witness management system for Crown Courts — ena...",
    "sector": "GovTech / Justice",
    "country": "UK",
    "status": "On Time",
    "contract": "Fixed Price",
    "technology": "",
    "compliance": "UK GDPR Article 10, Victims' Code 2020, Witness Charter, PSBAR WCAG 2.1 AA, GDS Service Standard, Domestic Violence Crime and Victims Act 2004, Cyber Essentials Plus",
    "challenge": "An HMCTS-contracted digital supplier building a pilot digital witness management system for Crown Courts — enabling witnesses and victims to receive digital notifications, choose evidence-in-chief format (live appearance, pre-recorded cross-examination, video link), and receive support service referrals. UK GDPR for victim/witness personal data, Victims' Code 2020, Witness Charter, GDS Service Standard, WCAG 2.1 AA (PSBAR), and the Domestic Violence, Crime and Victims Act 2004 were mandatory. Budget: £70,000.",
    "approach": "Victims' Code 2020 Digital Implementation: Victims' Code 2020: 12 rights for victims of crime. Key digital rights: Right 1 (information about progress of case), Right 3 (referral to support services within 5 working days), Right 8 (information about the trial). Digital notification: GOV.UK Notify SMS/email — case milestone notifications (charge authorised, hearing date set, trial outcome). Support service referral: automated referral within 5 working days of report (Victim Support, ISVA for sexual violence, IDVAs for domestic abuse — tailored by offence type). Pre-Recorded Cross-Examination (Section 28): Section 28 Youth Justice and Criminal Evidence Act 1999: vulnerable witnesses (under 18, mental health, sexual offence victims) can have cross-examination pre-recorded before trial. Platform: Section 28 eligibility assessment (special measure application), pre-recording appointment booking (HMCTS Booking Service API), digital evidence submission (upload pre-recording to platform → secure transfer to court), and trial substitute playback scheduling (clerk marks pre-recording for jury playback during trial). UK GDPR Victim Data — Highest Sensitivity: Victim data: personal data relating to criminal offences (Article 10 UK GDPR) — highest sensitivity. Processing basis: Article 6(1)(e) public task + Article 10 criminal offence data. Data minimisation: witness system receives only data necessary for witness management — not full prosecution case file. Access control: witness support officer sees their assigned witnesses only. Retention: witness contact data deleted 6 months after case conclusion (Victims' Code data management guidance). GDS Service Standard and Accessibility: GDS Service Assessment Beta pass criteria: user research with victims and witnesses (particularly vulnerable groups — trauma-informed research approach), accessibility (WCAG 2.1 AA + cognitive accessibility for distressed users), and performance (&lt; 3 second load time). ClickMasters designed with trauma-informed principles: clear, simple language, no unexpected questions, easy exit from process at any point, and explicit support information on every page. NVDA/VoiceOver testing with users who have a disability.",
    "results": "GDS Beta assessment: passed first attempt. Platform live at 12 weeks, £64,000 — under budget. Victims' Code Right 3 compliance (support referral within 5 working days): 97% (target: 90%). Case milestone notification delivery: 99.2% (SMS + email). Section 28 pre-recording bookings processed: 340 in pilot. Victim satisfaction with digital process: 4.1/5 (significant given inherent distress of criminal process). WCAG 2.1 AA: zero non-compliances. HMCTS extended pilot to 4 additional Crown Courts.",
    "clientQuote": "",
