    "technology": "",
    "compliance": "GMC Good Medical Practice, CQC registration (independent healthcare), HM Government Human Medicines Regulations 2012, UK GDPR Article 9, ICO health data guidance, WCAG 2.1 AA, Cyber Essentials Plus",
    "challenge": "A UK private GP network with 12 practices, 84 GPs, and 180,000 registered patients needed a unified digital platform — replacing phone-based appointment booking, paper prescription requests, and fragmented clinical notes. GMC (General Medical Council) clinical record standards, CQC registration (independent healthcare provider), UK GDPR Article 9 (health data), ICO guidance on health data, private prescription regulations (HM Government Human Medicines Regulations 2012), and WCAG 2.1 AA were mandatory. Budget: £110,000.",
    "approach": "Online Appointment Booking and Video Consultation: Appointment booking: patient portal (React PWA) — book available GP appointment (next available, preferred GP, or specific expertise). Appointment types: in-person (practice), telephone, and video (Whereby embedded video — GDPR-compliant EU data residency). GP availability: calendar integration (Microsoft Graph API — GP Outlook calendars synchronised to booking system). Automated reminders: GOV.UK Notify SMS 24 hours before appointment. DNA management: no-show tracking, automated rebooking offer, DNA policy (after 3 DNA without contact — patient warned). Private Prescription Workflow: HM Government Human Medicines Regulations 2012: private prescriptions require: (1) prescriber name, address, GMC number, (2) patient name, address, date of birth, (3) drug name (generic or brand), dose, quantity, (4) prescriber signature. Digital private prescription: GP completes structured prescription form → PDF generated (prescription format compliant with HMR 2012) → signed digitally (DocuSign — qualified electronic signature for GMC requirements) → patient receives prescription PDF → patient takes to any pharmacy. Controlled drugs: CD prescriptions require additional fields (maximum 28-day quantity, no electronic signature — paper required). Clinical Records and GMC Standards: GMC Good Medical Practice: clinical records must be clear, accurate, legible, and contemporaneous. Digital clinical record: SOAP notes (Subjective, Objective, Assessment, Plan) structured entry, read codes (Clinical Terms Version 3 — UK primary care standard), allergy and adverse reaction recording (mandatory), and medication history (BNF drug lookup — NHS Business Services Authority BNF API). Clinical audit: random 5% clinical record audit (GP Partners review notes for GMC standards compliance). Records retention: private GP records retained minimum 10 years post-last-consultation (BMA guidance). CQC Registration and Quality Evidence: CQC (Care Quality Commission): independent GP practices require CQC registration (regulated activity: diagnostic and screening procedures, treatment of disease). CQC Key Lines of Enquiry (KLOEs): Safe, Effective, Caring, Responsive, Well-led. Platform CQC evidence: appointment waiting time dashboard (Responsive evidence), clinical audit results (Effective), patient feedback survey (Caring — FFT equivalent), complaint management workflow (Safe). CQC inspection: platform evidence pack generated automatically — clinical audit, patient feedback, complaint resolution rates.",
    "results": "CQC registration confirmed. Platform live at 18 weeks, £102,000 — under budget. Online appointment booking adoption: 78% of appointments booked digitally (target: 60%). Video consultation: 34% of appointments now video (reduces practice overhead). DNA rate: 14.2% → 6.8% (SMS reminders). Private prescription digital: 94% (previously 100% paper). CQC inspection: Outstanding for Responsive, Good overall. Patient NPS: 82. GMC clinical record audit: 98.4% compliance (target: 95%).",
