    "id": "P1334",
    "slug": "govtech-local-authority-revenues-benefits",
    "title": "GovTech Local Authority Digital Revenues and Benefits Platform",
    "metaTitle": "GovTech Local Authority Digital Revenues and Benefits Platform — ClickMasters Case Study",
    "metaDesc": "A UK metropolitan borough council with 180,000 residents, £84M Council Tax revenue per year, and £42M Housing ...",
    "sector": "GovTech / Local Government",
    "country": "UK",
    "status": "On Time",
    "contract": "Fixed Price",
    "technology": "",
    "compliance": "GDS Service Standard (local government), UK GDPR, Local Government Finance Act 1992, Housing Benefit Regulations, DWP data sharing, WCAG 2.1 AA, Cyber Essentials Plus",
    "challenge": "A UK metropolitan borough council with 180,000 residents, £84M Council Tax revenue per year, and £42M Housing Benefit expenditure per year needed to modernise their revenues and benefits digital platform — replacing Northgate Revenues (legacy CR&amp;B system) with a modern cloud-native platform. GDS Service Standard (local government variant), UK GDPR, Universal Credit managed migration (Housing Benefit to Universal Credit — DWP data sharing), Council Tax legislation (Local Government Finance Act 1992), Housing Benefit regulations, and WCAG 2.1 AA were mandatory. Budget: £120,000.",
    "approach": "Council Tax Digital Service: Council Tax lifecycle: property owner/occupier registration → liability assessment (full charge, single person discount 25%, empty property premium, student exemption, SMI — Severe Mental Impairment — exemption) → annual bill generation → payment (Direct Debit, online, PayPoint) → reminder / summons workflow (reminder: 14 days after missed payment; summons: 7 days after reminder; liability order: magistrates court). Digital service: online Council Tax account (view bill, set up Direct Debit, apply for discount/exemption), GOV.UK Notify (bill notifications, reminders), and Valuation Office Agency (VOA) API (Council Tax band lookup by property address — UKVP reference). Housing Benefit and Universal Credit Migration: Housing Benefit (HB): local authority-administered means-tested benefit for rent. DWP Managed Migration: existing HB claimants migrated to Universal Credit (UC) by DWP — local authority must process final HB payment and close claim when UC migration notice received. DWP data sharing: ATLAS (Automated Transfer to Local Authorities System) — DWP sends UC migration data to local authority via ATLAS API. Council Tax Reduction (CTR): CTR replaces Council Tax Benefit (abolished 2013) — each council has its own CTR scheme (statutory minimum protection for pensioners, local scheme for working-age claimants). Automated CTR assessment: income data from DWP ATLAS → CTR entitlement calculation → Council Tax bill adjustment. Single Customer View: Single Customer View: one record per resident linking Council Tax, Housing Benefit, CTR, Business Rates, and other council services. Address matching: Royal Mail PAF (Postcode Address File) + UPRN (Unique Property Reference Number) — every property in the UK has a UPRN. Resident matching: Name + DOB + address matching to prevent duplicate records. GDPR Article 5(1)(e): data must not be kept longer than necessary — single customer view retention schedule (active records retained whilst service obligation exists, inactive records deleted after 7 years — local government audit requirement). GDS Local Government Assessment: GDS Service Standard applies to local government digital services funded by central government grants. Assessment requirements: (1) user research with residents including vulnerable populations (benefits claimants — often vulnerable), (2) accessible design (WCAG 2.1 AA — Council Tax digital service used by elderly residents, disabled residents), (3) GOV.UK Design System components, (4) GOV.UK Pay for online payment (PCI-DSS handled by HMRC/GOV.UK Pay — council's SAQ-A), (5) GOV.UK Notify for communications. ClickMasters GDS evidence pack produced throughout build — not retrospectively compiled before assessment.",
    "results": "GDS assessment passed (Live). Platform live at 22 weeks, £112,000 — under budget. Council Tax digital accounts: 68,400 activated (38% of residents — target: 30%). Direct Debit take-up: 72% (previously 58%). Council Tax reminder letters: GOV.UK Notify (98% digital — 2% paper for residents without email). Housing Benefit to UC migration: 100% automated ATLAS processing (3,400 claimants migrated — zero manual processing). CTR automated assessment: 94.2% (5.8% require manual review). WCAG 2.1 AA: zero non-compliances. Resident satisfaction: 4.2/5.",
    "clientQuote": "",
