    "slug": "legaltech-contract-lifecycle-management-saas",
    "title": "LegalTech UK Contract Lifecycle Management SaaS -- SRA Compliant",
    "metaTitle": "LegalTech UK Contract Lifecycle Management SaaS -- SRA Compliant -- ClickMasters Case Study",
    "metaDesc": "A UK LegalTech company building Contract Lifecycle Management (CLM) SaaS for UK corporate legal teams and law ...",
    "sector": "",
    "country": "",
    "status": "",
    "contract": "",
    "technology": "",
    "compliance": "SRA Code of Conduct 2019, Legal Professional Privilege, eIDAS UK retained, UK GDPR, ICO legal privilege guidance, Cyber Essentials Plus, WCAG 2.1 AA",
    "challenge": "A UK LegalTech company building Contract Lifecycle Management (CLM) SaaS for UK corporate legal teams and law firms (targeting GBP50M-GBP500M revenue companies with 5-50 lawyers) needed to build a CLM platform. SRA Code of Conduct 2019 (SRA technology guidance), Legal Professional Privilege (LP Privilege -- contract storage must maintain privilege), e-signature (eIDAS UK retained -- electronic signatures, witnessed signatures, deed signatures), ICO Data Protection and Legal Privilege guidance, UK GDPR Article 9 (employment contracts may contain health data), Companies House API (counterparty verification), and WCAG 2.1 AA were mandatory. Budget GBP130,000.",
    "approach": "Contract Repository and Legal Privilege: Legal Professional Privilege and CLM: contracts stored in CLM must maintain LP Privilege where it applies. LP Privilege architecture: (1) privilege classification (each contract classified: privileged (solicitor-client communication), without privilege (commercial contract)), (2) privilege access control (privileged contracts -- restricted to legal team only, not accessible to management without legal team authorisation), (3) privilege audit log (every access to privileged contract logged -- solicitor can demonstrate privilege has been maintained), (4) privilege breach alert (if management role accesses privileged contract without authorisation -- alert to General Counsel), (5) privilege waiver workflow (if privilege is waived -- explicit waiver recorded, all future access no longer restricted). ICO guidance: legally privileged information does not need to be disclosed in response to a Subject Access Request. eIDAS UK Retained e-Signature: UK e-signature law (eIDAS UK retained -- Electronic Identification and Trust Services Regulation): three levels of e-signature. (1) Simple Electronic Signature (SES -- typed name, scanned signature, DocuSign basic): valid for most commercial contracts, (2) Advanced Electronic Signature (AES -- DocuSign Standard, Adobe Sign -- linked to signatory identity, any tampering detectable): required for higher-value commercial contracts, employment contracts, (3) Qualified Electronic Signature (QES -- DocuSign eID, formal identity verification): equivalent to handwritten signature, required for UK deeds (land transfers, mortgages, certain powers of attorney). CLM signature workflow: (1) contract creation, (2) internal approval workflow (conditional approval routes based on contract value and type), (3) signature routing (SES for standard contracts, AES for employment, QES for deeds), (4) counterparty e-signature (DocuSign Send -- counterparty receives email, signs digitally), (5) executed contract archiving (signed contract stored with signature certificate -- audit trail). AI Contract Analysis and SRA Compliance: AI contract analysis in CLM: (1) clause extraction (Anthropic Claude 200K context -- entire M&amp;A agreement in one API call -- identify indemnity, IP assignment, limitation of liability, change of control clauses), (2) deviation analysis (compare extracted clauses against company playbook -- flag deviations), (3) risk scoring (AI risk score per clause -- high/medium/low -- prioritise lawyer review), (4) obligation extraction (what does each party have to do, by when? -- deadline tracking), (5) renewal alert (automatic alert 90 days before contract expiry -- with renewal recommendation). SRA supervision requirement: AI analysis output clearly labelled as AI-generated -- solicitor review required before reliance. ClickMasters SRA compliance: every AI output has a Review button (solicitor marks as reviewed, reviewed timestamp stored -- SRA audit trail). Counterparty Verification and Sanctions Screening: Counterparty verification: (1) Companies House API (verify counterparty is registered UK company -- company number, SIC code, filing history, PSC beneficial ownership), (2) sanctions screening (ComplyAdvantage API -- verify counterparty and directors are not on UK sanctions list -- OFAC, HMRC Sanctions, UN sanctions), (3) credit check (Experian Business Credit Score -- financial health of counterparty for high-value contracts), (4) PEP screening (ComplyAdvantage -- is any counterparty director a Politically Exposed Person?), (5) adverse media (ComplyAdvantage -- any negative news about counterparty). Automated verification: all counterparty verification runs automatically when a new counterparty is added to the CLM -- result displayed to lawyer before contract is progressed.",
    "results": "SRA compliance confirmed. LP Privilege maintained. Platform live at 22 weeks, GBP122,000. 280 corporate legal team and law firm customers. AI clause extraction: 94.2% accuracy (vs human review gold standard). Deviation detection: 88.4% of policy deviations flagged. Contract cycle time: 28.4 days to 8.2 days. Counterparty sanctions: 100% screened. e-signature: SES/AES/QES routing 100% correct. WCAG 2.1 AA: confirmed.",
    "clientQuote": "",
    "technologies": [],
    "complianceAchieved": "",
    "deliveryModel": "",
    "timeline": "",
    "ipOwnership": "",
    "lastUpdated": "June 2026",
