    "technology": "",
    "compliance": "DTAC all 5 domains, DCB0129, MHRA Class I, UK GDPR Article 9, NHS Talking Therapies integration standards, WCAG 2.1 AA, Cyber Essentials",
    "challenge": "A UK digital mental health company wanted to build a self-guided CBT (Cognitive Behavioural Therapy) app for mild-to-moderate anxiety and depression, integrated with NHS Talking Therapies (formerly IAPT — Improving Access to Psychological Therapies). NICE guidelines for digital CBT (DClinPsy-supervised), DTAC all 5 domains, NHS Talking Therapies outcome measures (PHQ-9 and GAD-7 questionnaires), MHRA Class I medical device registration, and UK GDPR Article 9 for mental health data were mandatory. Budget: £80,000.",
    "approach": "NICE-Compliant Digital CBT Content: NICE guideline CG91 (depression) and CG113 (generalised anxiety): digital CBT must be based on established CBT protocols. Content developed under supervision of DClinPsy (Doctoral Clinical Psychologist) — evidenced in DTAC Domain 1. Content modules: psychoeducation, cognitive restructuring, behavioural activation, relaxation techniques, relapse prevention. Safety planning: crisis resources prominently available at all times — not buried in settings. NHS Talking Therapies Integration: NHS Talking Therapies (formerly IAPT) referral API: self-referral submission to local IAPT service (the app supplements, not replaces, NHS therapy). PHQ-9 (depression) and GAD-7 (anxiety) outcome measures: administered in-app weekly, data shared with NHS Talking Therapies clinical record via FHIR R4 QuestionnaireResponse. NHS Login integration: patient identity and consent for data sharing with NHS Talking Therapies service. UK GDPR Article 9 — Mental Health Data: Mental health data is Article 9 special category. Lawful basis: explicit consent (not public task — this is a commercial app with NHS integration). Granular consent: separate consent for each data category (CBT exercise data, outcome measure scores, sharing with NHS Talking Therapies). Right to erasure: immediate deletion of all mental health data on request — with clear explanation that NHS Talking Therapies data may be retained separately by NHS. AES-256 field-level encryption for all Article 9 data. DTAC Domain 1 Clinical Safety — Mental Health: DCB0129 CSO: DClinPsy as Clinical Safety Officer (mental health domain expertise required). Highest hazard: app used as substitute for crisis care — mitigated by prominent, accessible crisis resources (Samaritans, Crisis text line) at every screen and in every push notification about mood worsening. Safety monitoring: significant PHQ-9 score worsening triggers in-app safety message and push notification with crisis resources.",
    "results": "NHS App Library listed at 16 weeks, £74,000 — under budget. DTAC approved all 5 domains (first submission). MHRA Class I registered. NHS Talking Therapies integration: live in 12 CCG/ICB areas at launch. 4,200 app users in 6 months. PHQ-9 improvement (reduction ≥5 points): 64% of users completing 8-week programme. Safety monitoring: 34 safety alerts generated — all actioned with crisis resource delivery. NICE evidence base review: commended by NHS England digital mental health team.",
