    "contract": "Fixed Price",
    "technology": "",
    "compliance": "HMLR Business Gateway, HMRC SDLT, SRA Code of Conduct, SRA Accounts Rules, UK GDPR, Land Registration Act 2002, Cyber Essentials",
    "challenge": "A UK conveyancing law firm completing 4,200 property transactions per year wanted to automate their conveyancing process — reducing the 14-week average transaction time, eliminating repetitive data entry, and meeting the Ministry of Housing's Digital Conveyancing initiative standards. HMLR Digital Registration Service (AP1/TR1 electronic lodgement), SDLT (Stamp Duty Land Tax) HMRC API, Land Registry searches, and SRA professional obligations were the primary requirements. Budget: £95,000.",
    "approach": "HMLR Digital Registration Service: HMLR DRS (Digital Registration Service): electronic AP1 (Application to Register) and TR1 (Transfer of Whole) lodgement via HMLR Business Gateway API. Pre-lodgement validation: automated validation against HMLR requirements before submission (reducing rejection rate). Title register retrieval: OS1 (Official Search of Whole) automated via Business Gateway. Priority period tracking: 30 business day priority period alert management. SDLT Automation: HMRC SDLT (Stamp Duty Land Tax) return API: SDLT1 return auto-populated from transaction data (purchase price, property type, buyer status — first-time buyer, additional property). SDLT calculation engine: implements all SDLT bands, first-time buyer relief, multiple dwellings relief, non-residential rates. Submission via HMRC API with reference number retrieval. SDLT certificate generation (required for HMLR registration). Property Search Automation: Local authority searches: automated ordering via SearchFlow API (connecting to all UK local authorities). Environmental searches: Groundsure API. Drainage searches: utility company APIs (where available) or SearchFlow. Search result integration: results automatically attached to matter and key issues extracted (planning enforcement notices, road adoption status, contamination). SLA tracking: search SLAs monitored with escalation alerts. SRA Professional Obligations in Automation: SRA Code of Conduct: automated processes must not substitute for solicitor judgement on matters of legal advice. Architecture principle: automation handles data collection, form population, and submission — solicitor reviews and approves before every submission. Audit trail: every automated action attributed to the system, every approval attributed to the named solicitor. SRA accounts rules: client money in HMLR transactions tracked per matter automatically.",
    "results": "System live at 16 weeks, £88,000 — under budget. Average transaction time: 14 weeks → 9.2 weeks. HMLR rejection rate: 12% → 1.8% (pre-submission validation). SDLT errors: zero (automated calculation replaced manual spreadsheet). Search ordering: same-day automated vs 2–3 day manual. SRA accounts audit: zero findings. Conveyancer time per transaction: 4.2 hours → 2.1 hours (50% reduction). HMLR commended firm in Digital Conveyancing Initiative review.",
