    "slug": "legaltech-document-automation-commercial-law",
    "title": "LegalTech Document Automation Platform — UK Commercial Law Firm",
    "metaTitle": "LegalTech Document Automation Platform — UK Commercial Law Firm — ClickMasters Case Study",
    "metaDesc": "A UK top-20 commercial law firm with 420 fee earners completing 28,000 documents per year (NDAs, employment co...",
    "sector": "LegalTech / Document Automation",
    "country": "UK",
    "status": "On Time",
    "contract": "Fixed Price",
    "technology": "",
    "compliance": "SRA Code of Conduct, Legal Professional Privilege, UK GDPR, Law Society AI guidelines, eIDAS (UK retained), Cyber Essentials",
    "challenge": "A UK top-20 commercial law firm with 420 fee earners completing 28,000 documents per year (NDAs, employment contracts, shareholder agreements, commercial leases) wanted to build a document automation platform — replacing manual template creation with intelligent document assembly. SRA document storage obligations, UK GDPR for client personal data in documents, Legal Professional Privilege data handling, and The Law Society's guidelines on AI in legal practice were the requirements. Budget: £130,000.",
    "approach": "Document Assembly Engine: Template engine: HotDocs-replacement built on Docxtemplater (Node.js DOCX template engine). Template logic: conditional clauses (if English law, include Choice of Law clause; if cross-border, include GDPR Article 46 transfer mechanism), variable substitution (party names, dates, governing law, jurisdiction), and nested template fragments (insert relevant boilerplate clauses based on deal type). Template library: 148 templates across 12 practice areas, migrated from HotDocs legacy system. Legal AI Clause Library: AI-assisted clause selection: Anthropic Claude API (RAG over firm's precedent library) — suggest appropriate clauses for deal-specific requirements. Lawyer review required: every AI-suggested clause reviewed by qualified solicitor before insertion — no automated clause selection. AI disclaimer: in-app notice that AI-suggested clauses are for guidance only and require legal review. Law Society guidelines compliance: firm's AI policy documented and circulated to fee earners. SRA Document Retention and LPP Handling: SRA Code of Conduct: client documents retained for minimum 6 years post-matter close. LPP isolation: documents in the platform are covered by LPP — no document content visible to platform administrators. Encrypted at rest: AES-256 per document. Access audit: every document access logged (who, when, what action) — SRA inspection ready. Matter isolation: fee earner can only access documents for their own matters or matters they have been explicitly granted access to. eSignature Integration and Execution: DocuSign eSignature integration: document sent for signature from platform, signature events tracked, executed document stored back in platform. Electronic signature validity: Regulation (EU) No 910/2014 (eIDAS) applies to UK contracts (retained in UK law) — simple electronic signatures valid for most commercial contracts. Qualified Electronic Signatures (QES): supported via DocuSign for contracts requiring higher assurance (company articles, land transfers).",
    "results": "Platform live at 18 weeks, £122,000 — under budget. Document assembly time: average 4.2 hours → 22 minutes. Template utilisation: 89% of documents assembled from templates (vs 45% on legacy HotDocs). Partner review time: reduced 34% (better first-draft quality from AI clause suggestions). SRA file review: document retention compliance confirmed at 100%. Law Society AI guidelines: firm's AI policy reviewed and approved by the Professional Ethics committee.",
